150	/*!
151	 * \brief For each request, we maintain its "request state" in the
152	 * engine. Generally, the state of a request contains the information
153	 * of the request's generation at the current moment, including
154	 * the generated token ids, the grammar handler, etc.
155	 *
156	 * When a request has multiple parallel generations (e.g., the field
157	 * `n` of its generation config is more than 1), each generation will
158	 * have different states all the time.
159	 *
160	 * Therefore, to better support parallel generations, we denote the
161	 * state of a single generation as a "RequestStateEntry" instance,
162	 * and denote the state of a request's all generations using a vector,
163	 * named as a "RequestState" instance.
164	 *
165	 * A request's all state entries are organized as a tree structure
166	 * when there are parallel generations.
167	 * - the request input has the root status entry,
168	 * - each parallel generation is a child of the root.
169	 * This tree structure may be further extended to more complicated
170	 * cases in the future. As of now, for the case of `n > 1`, there
171	 * will be (n + 1) entries in total. In a "RequestState", the root
172	 * entry always has index 0. And we guarantee that the entry order
173	 * from the vector begin to the end is always a topological order
174	 * of the tree.
175	 */
176	
177	/*! \brief Request state status. */
178	enum class RequestStateStatus : int {
179	  kPending = 0,
180	  kAlive = 1,
181	  kFinished = 2,
182	};
